{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580382/1945081701/0983.xml":{"full_text":"Page Four_________________ __\nTOLEDO UttON JuURNAL\nOfficial Publication\nToledo Industrial Union Council\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nPobtished every Friday by Local No. 12\ntJAW-CIO.. 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nMember of American Labor Press Association\nFditoP .................Melvin Schultz\nManaging ttffot.................... O- Record\nAdvertising Manager Burny Zawodny\nBoard of Trustees\nMelvin Schultz, Thomas Burke,\nRandolph Gray\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nOne year, by mail, in advance\nEntered at the Toledo. Ohio, post office as\nsecond class matter under the act of\nAug. 24. 1912.\nPeace And The Future\nJapan has been defeated. The war is\nover.\nAfrican workers, and the sons and\ndaugimrs of American workers, have\nmade uur victory over Naxiism, Fascism\nand Japism possible.\nPeace for which the peoples of all na\ntions have longed can and will be secured\nif the principles for which this war was\nfought and won are not lost to sight in the\ngrasping after postwar opportunities by\nthose in a position to place their own self\ninterest ahead of the welfare of the ma\njority of the people.\nDespite the victory, none is so con\nfused that they believe the forces against\nwhich we have directed our all-out en\nergies for the past months of war are elim\ninated forever. Again and again we must\nremind ourselves that our future peace,\nhappiness and security require our eternal\nvigilance if we would avext tl^e blood and\nwaste of armed warfare.\nToday, the majority of the people of\nthis country face the realities of a peace\ntime world. We are aware of the needs of\nour own people and those of other coun\ntries. We know that we must all put our\nshoulder to the wheel and cooperate in the\nenterprise of peace as we applied our\nenergies to the tasks of war.\nIt is unavoidable that ih making the\ntransition from war to peace that tempo\nrary large scale unemployment will result,\nbut it is also true that the reconversion to\na peacetime economy can be greatly short\nened if industry and our government will\ncooperate with labor.\nWe recognize, of course, that not every\nemployer will give the reconversion ef\nfort sincere cooperation. Some W'ill at\ntempt to use it to their own advantage,\nwhile others will make the occasion one\nfor seeking to maintain the checks which\nlabor placed upon itself during the war\nyears.\nWhat occurs in the reconversion period\nand after full scale production is resumed\nis going to be conditioned to a consider\nable extent upon how wisely management\nacts in carrying out its part of the pro\ngram and, of course, upon the amount of\ncontrol exercised by government.\nThat the results of this war must he\ntotally different from those which fol\nlowed World War I requires but little ex\nplanation. Organized labor with growing\npolitical consciousness and an appeal to\nthe vast majority of the people that can\nnot be denied, will not stand hitched if\ngovernment and management stall and\nbungle the job of reconversion which lies\nimmediately before them.\nNor will the servicemen long remain\nsilent if they return to their homes,\n5,000,000 strong, in the next 12 months, to\ndiscover that something has slipped and\nthe promises made to them were hut\nempty pledges of an alarmed government\nand profit starved industrial overlords.\nThis is the occasion, fully as serious\nand important to the people of America as\nthe day when the war was thrust upon\nus, when we must rise in unison to meet\nand beat the problems which now confront\nus. We must face the situation with the\nsame boldness and courage with which we\nrolled up our sleeves and went to work to\ndefeat the enemies of our country who now\nlie in abject defeat before the irresistible\ncounter attack of a free people.\nThis is not an occasion for fear, but one\nfor satisfaction and decisive action. It is\na time when we must resolve to forever\neliminate the paradox which gives full\nemployment in time of war, and want in\nthe midst of plenty in time of peace. This\nis the peace which still remains to be won.\n\u201cThe great malady of public life is coward\nice. Most men are not untrue, but they are\nafraid. Most of the errors of public life, if\nmy observation is to be trusted, conic not be\ncause men are morally bad, but because they\nare afraid of somebody. God knows why they\nshould be ft is generally shadows they are\nalxa of.\u201d\n-\u2014Woodrow Wilson.\nOf Senator Pankin, The C.T.O. News, says,\n\u201cWhy pick on Senator Rankin? He is only ono,\ndrip in the puddle, one jerk in the spasm that\nconvulses Congress.\u201d\n\u201cI will testify conscientiously to the mag\nnificent contribution towards our war program\nmade by the great body of organized labor,\u201d\n\u2014-Vice Admiral Ben Moreell,\nChief of Seabees.\nThe farmer, like the city worker, has been\ntaking it in the neck for years. Proof: In 1933\nAmerican farmers received 38 5% of the con\nsumer\u2019s dollar while processors and distribu\ntors received 61.5% But in Denmark these\npercentages were reversed\u2014farmers getting\n63.4% while the middlemen got 36.6%\nFew workers realize that organized labor\nin America led the way to a free and demo\ncratic educational system. As early as 1829\nLabor released a school program calling for\nmore schools, free schools, and an election\nschool boards.\nWhat\u2019s\nBy\nEdward Duck\nWith The\n45th Infantry\nin Germany\nTHEY WON\u2019T TALK\nFRIEDBERG, Germany, Re\nturning servicemen are being\ndeluged with queries about\ncombat. Most of them either\nshut up like clams or art\nfully maneuver the conver\nsation to another subject. They\nhad enough \u201cwar talk\u201d where\nthey were. It is something\nthey are trying to forget.\n\u201cWhat's it like?\u201d \u201cDid\nyou kill any Germans?\u201d\n\u201cWere you very scared?\u201d\n\u201cDid any shells land Hear\nyou? These are standard\nquestions which millions of\nloved ones and friends are\neveryday throwing at veterans\ndischarged on points or home\nfor thirty days before being\nredemployed to the Pacific.\nIt\u2019s no sin to ask these ques\ntions. But if he doesn\u2019t answer\nyou immediately and cheer\nfully, don\u2019t persist. Many com\nbat men are hesitant to discuss\nbattle experiences because\nthey are trying to close the\npages of a book more eerie\nthan anything Edgar Allen\nPoe ever conceived. Front line\ncombat is unpleasant beyond\nall human understanding. It\nis hell.\nIt is not the exploding of\nmortars and artillery, nor the\nnearby of the sniper\u2019s bullet,\nnor the rapid tattoo of a\ncamoflaged machine gun that\nis recalled by the fellow who\nrelates his experiences. He re\nmembers more than that.\nHE REMEMBERS\nHe remembers how dead\ntired he was, how his stomach\nfelt after weeks of K-ration\nmeals, how his only clothes\nwere on his back, soaking wet\nand worn for weeks at a\ntime. He remembers how his.\nfeet wore cold and numb, how.\nhis fingers were almost frozen\nto the point where he could\nhardly pull the trigger of his\nrille. -He remembers seeing\nhis comrades bleed and die in\nthe confusion of battle, often\ntimes mistakenly fired upon\nby his own buddies.\nHa remembers burning\nhomes, screaming, hysterical\nwomen and children, artillery\nbehind him and airplanes be*\nfore him and above him. He\nremembers that he hadn\u2019t slept\nfor three or four days, ex\ncepting two or three hours\nspent in a cold barn,\nHe remembers all these\nthings in one composite re\ncollection, and as he relates\nhis experiences you can watch\nhis eyes move quickly about\nthe room, listen to his words\ncome faster and faster, and his\nvoice become louder and more\nexcited. Each succeeding event\nevent is re-lived as he re\ncounts the happenings so vivid\nin his mind.\nPREFERS SILENCE\nThis is why he may prefer\nnot to talk about it. Combat\nis something you can discuss\nfor hours and hours, but never\nrealize just what it is like un\nless you are in it. To see\nbrave men go to pieces is not\na pleasant sight, but this thing\nwhich the late Ernie Pyle\ncalled \u201ccombat fatigue\u201d can\nmake a tough soldier sob and\ncry like a baby\u2014and not be\ncause he's afraid to die, either.\nThe nervous system of the\nhuman being will stand just\nso much wear and tear. When\nthe breaking point is reached,\nit is beyond any control.\nWhen war\u2019s bloody hand\nreaches out for you, when you\nturn hot and cold at the same\ntime, when you think that this\nmoment is your last, there is\nbut one thing you will do, and\nthat\u2019s pray\u2014-like you never\nprayed before. When this time\ncomes the brave and the weak\nare not too far apart in com\nparison.\nWho are the heros? Not\nthe men you find playing the\nrole in fiction, in the operettas,\nor in the movies. They are\nthat skinny kid with glasses\nyou used to pick on a few\nyears back, that fellow you\ncalled \u201csissy\u201d, or the boy who\nused to sell newspapers in\nyour neighborhood. They\naren\u2019t necessarily \u201ctough guys\u201d\nin civilian life. They probably\nminded their own business\nmost of the time. A lot of\n\u201ctough guys\u201d han\u00a3 back when\nthe push is on\u00ab\nW\u00ab0 TM\u00bbe\nWIU ALWAYS\nBE WARS\nrt:\n1\nW\nIt\u2019s News\nTo Me...\nBy O. Pecord\nCONFUSION\nDefeat of Japan announced last Tuesday byPresident Tro\nman is still so recent that the confusion resulting from it had\nnot been pieced out to the point where we can get a clear picture\nof what is happening, or what is going to occur in the immediate\nfuture.\nTwo things are certain, (1.) Large scale unemployment is\nabout to b^gin and apparently will continue lintil reconversion\nhas been completed. (2.) That Congress is playing its usual cuni\nbersome, placid and stupid role in an emergency which is about\nto affect the lives and living of millions of people.\nWhat labor has feared has now taken place. It is an ac\ncomplished fact'just as pointed in its challenge as was Hitler\u2019s\noccupation of the land of the other nations prior to the invasion\nof Poland.\nTriumph to American arms brings before the workers and\nlabor leaders of this country a new set of problems which must\nbe absolutely met and dealt with. The sudden termination of the\nwar finds us in the position which Many feared would occur.\nWe are not. prepared fox peace.\nSOMEBODY KNEW\nSomebody in our government must have known the possi\nbilities contained in the atomic bomb. They must have been\naware of the fact that this revolutionary weapon contained the\npossibilities of forcing a quick termination to the war, yet, de\nspite this knowledge, Army and Navy heads obstructed recon\nversion and civilian production at a time when we could have\ngained at least two or three months in preparing for normal\npeacetime production.\nSomebody in the administration must have realized that the\natomic bomb would ruin the Japs\u2019 war effort and send them\nscurrying to save their yellow necks from complete destruction,\nstill, nobody made any attempt to prevent the hot and weary\nCongress from disbanding and seeking cooler climes where tired\nsecond-rate statesmen could relax while the peace crisis was in\nthe making.\nAnd so 'we find ourselves in the midst of a situation upon\nwhich government so far remains silent, or tells us the things\nthat it seems to believe we want to hear. Who the hell cares\nif gasoline rationing is lifted if they are jobless and trying to\neke out a bare subsistance upon a lousy $15 to $23 a week?\nHow much gasoline will a guy buy who is trying to raise a fam\nily on the disgraceful pittance allowed by a grateful state to\nthose who worked six and seven days a week and in many\ncases 10 or more hours daily?\nWho cares if canned fruits and vegetables are point ffee\nwhen they face the prospect of immediate loss of their jobs and\nare acutely aware that they have just enough war bonds put\naside to tide them over for a three or four-week period of job\nlessness?\nWhat young guy over 26 years of age gets excited when ne\nIs told that he need have no further fear of being drafted when\nhe is about on tlie verge of being bumped off his job together\nwith thousands of other young fellows?\nWhat soldier'faces the prospect of being discharged wfth\nconfidence and satisfaction when lie realizes that he is craning\nhome to a situation which may be even worse than his father\nfaced following the end of the war to make the world cafe for\ndemocracy?\nWill RE IS CONGRESS\nWhy is the reconvening of Congress held off until Septem\nber 5th? If this country were attacked today by an enemy there\nwould be no difficulty in getting the legislative louts back to\ntheir posts in a hurry to declare war upon the aggressor and\nand once more promise everything to the boys and the workers.\nAnd is unemployment and the misery and want which go with\nit not an aggressor?\nAll of these things are evidence that the war Is surely over.\nAll of these stalling tactics. This vast gob of silence which issues\nfrom Washington, this indecision and uncertainty which has\nfallen upon us this early in the peace game is almost enough to\nmake even the most trusting ponder and ask questions. It looks\nlike we are on the march to that never-never-land of \u201cnor\nmalcy\u201d for which one President gave his life\" and for which our\nlords-of-all-they-survey once more seem to be bent.\nYes, the war is over. Congress proves it. Silence proves It.\nThe calm of a two-day holiday before the storm proves it. The\nactions of the bigwigs proves it. The facts of past history prove\nit We are on our way. But are we going?\nIt takes more than 44 months of unhealthy wartime proa\nperity to make the American people forget the years which pre\nceded the battles of World War II. It takes more than 52 hours\npay and a case of beer in the house to remove their memories\nfrom the unemployment of the prewar years. It will only take\nthem a few weeks to rekindle those memories and in the recall\ning determine that never again will they stand by and look at\nthemselves deteriorating in the dry rot of unemployment and\nfeel the deadening fingers of hunger grasp their bellies.\nThese are not the words of a wild-eyed radical or a Marx\nist, but the sentiments of the average American who now awaits\ncalmly for his government to announce that there shall not be\nanother depression, not even a temporary one, in a land which\nbad the brains and genius to give the aggressor nati?,\u00a3\u00a3 head\nstart and beat them at their own game.\ne\n-m\nI\nTHE TOLEDO UNION JOURNAL.\n\u25a0kX\nMAYBE\nFROM THE RANKS\nw\nK.i\neta\nWashin 'Moil\nLaborReport\nBy Bradford V. Carter,\nLPA\nColumnist\nRUMORS WPB\nAs this column is being\nwritten Washington is a hot\nhouse of rumors on the im\nminent end of the Japanese\nWar. The way in which of\nficial Washington responds to\na situation of great urgency is\ntypified in the fact that on the\nday which the end of the war\nmay come, it has just gotten\naround to announcing a policy\non reconversion.\nProbably because the Meafl\nCommittee had some caustic\nthings to say about the lack\nof progress in reconversion,\nPresident Truman issued a\nfive-point program for the in\nstruction of the War Produc\ntion Board. Underlying the\nTruman policy statement is\nalso a running controversy\nbetween Price Administrator\nBowles and WPB Chairman\nKrug.\nBowles felt that WPB con\ntrols of one kind or another\nwere indispensable to the\nmaintenance of the price stab\nilization program. Krug want\ned to get rid of WPB controls\nwithout reference to prices,\nwages or anything else.\nOne thing is clear\u2014and that\nis that the President of the\nUnited States wants the WPB\nto assume some reponsibility\nin easing the economy back\nto a peacetime footing. Ever\nsince Krug displaced Donald\nNelson, there has been an in\ncreasing apprehension on the\npart of labor that the current\nWPB chairman was inordi\nnately anxious to end controls\nirrespective of the effect of\nthis policy on the transition\nto a peacetime economy.\nOPPOSE CONTROLS\nConsidering the fact that\nWPB topside is opposed to\ngovernment controls after VJ\nday, considerable doubt is in\norder about the enthusiasm\nwhich will be demonstrated in\ncarrying through the Presi\ndent\u2019s policies. The story cir\nculating in Washington circles\nis that Krug is peeved at the\nfact that he was not made di\nrector of the Office of War\nMobilization and Reconversion\nto replace Fred Vinson. And\nthat this accounts for his cur\nrent coolness to the idea of\nWPB\u2019s positive role in recon\nversion.\nThe President\u2019s letter to\nKrug does not spell out in\ngreat detail the kinds of things\nwhich WPB can do. Labor\npeople in Washington, how\never are clear in their own\nminds what the function of\nWPB can be.\nIn the first place, labor feels\nthat the WPB authority to\ngrant priorities and allocations\nshould be used to prevent un\nemployment in the places\nwhere it is likely to hit the\nhardest.\nSecond, labor feels that\nWPB should use Its authority\nto assist in the acquisition of\nbottleneck items, where such\nitems are holding up full util\nization of facilities and man\npower in particular plants.\nFor example, here is a refrig\nerator manufacturer who is\nbeing held up because he can\u2019t\nget fractional horsepowers\nmotors. The WPB in this case,\nit is proposed, should step in\nOn The\nBeam\nBy\nClayton\nFountain\nLet me be one of the first\nto utter thanks that the British\nLabor Party took over in Eng\nland before we uncovered the\natomic bomb.\nAccording to the scanty in\nformation released by the au\nthorities, American and British\nscientists toiled together to un\nlock this miracle of our time,\nand we must asr\u2014e that the\nsecret formula for unleashing\natomic power is held jointly\nby the two countries.\nHad Churchill and the Tor\nies stayed in power in England,\nthe control of this terrible\nweapon would, have been\nplaced in the hands of two\ncountries in which the power\nof government was held large\nly by capitalist-minded politi\ncians.\nIf this had happened, I\nwould not have cared to wager\na dime on democracy\u2019s chance\nof survival in the post-war\nworld.\nPUSHED TOWARD\nIMPERIALISM\nA substantial section of the\nbanking and manufacturing\nfraternity in this country have\nbeen pushing America in the\ndirection of imperialism dur\ning this war.\nThey are the boys who have\ninsisted most loudly that the\nU. S. must keep the far-flung\naviation and naval bases built\nduring the war. They have per\nsistently demanded the demo\nlition of German industrial\npower. And they have quietly\nbut firmly backed the cam\npaign for peace-time conscript\ntion of American youth.\nFinally, these are the same\nboys who are sabotaging the\ndemand for full employment,\nand offering, as a counter-pro\nposal, the idea that we can\nattain prosperity through the'\nmedium of an expanded' for\neign trade.\nSINGLE PURPOSE\nThe single purpose behind\nall this was, and is, the de*\ntermination of the big-time\ncapitalist clique in this coun\ntry to bail out their faltering\neconomic system through ex\npansion of American foreign\ntrade under the protection of\nU. S. mlitary power.\nThat is why they wanted us\nto keep our war-time military\nbases in distant parts of the\nworld. That is why they want\ned German industry destroyed\n\u2014so as to eliminate it as a\ncompetitive factor in the post\nwar scramble for markets.\nThat is why they wanted\nus to adopt peace-time mili\ntary conscription, in order to\ngive them the power with\nwhich to extend their com\nmercial invasion of the mar\nkets of lesser nations.\nIn short, the whole scheme\nwas based on the notion that\nthe United States should use\nits military power to under\nwrite and guarantee the reap\ning of profits in global trade\ncontrolled by tAmerican cap\nitalists.\nTORY SYMPATHY\nOf course, the British Tories\nwere deeply in sympathy with\nthis scheme. It fell right in\nwith the pattern they have\nused for decades to bolster up\ntheir own capitalist regime. In\ncompany with their American\nbrethren of the counting\nhouses, the British capitalists\nforesaw an era of Anglo\nAmerican domination of world\ncommerce, which they expect\ned to insure their profits for\na few more years.\nWe can thank our lucky\nstars that the common people\nof England had the courage\nand the good sense to vote the\nLabor Party into power, and\nthus nip this imperialistic plot\nin the bud.\nWith the British Labor Gov\nernment sharing control of the\natomic bomb, we have some\nassurance that this diabolic\ndevice will not be used to\nbludgeon the rest of the world\ninto acceptance of the rule of\nAnglo-American imperialism,\nand order a manufacturer of\nfractional horsepower motors\nto give precedence to this or\nder over the order, say, of a\nproducer of pari-mutuel ma\nchines for the race tracks.\nWPB AUTHORITY\nWPB can use its authority\nin still another connection. It\ncan prevent the big boys from\nhogging up the supply of short\nitems such as sheet steel, by\nvirtue of their superior finan\ncial position.\nFinally, WPB controls must\nbe meshed in with price stab\nilization needs which is what\nMr. Bowles has been talking\nabout.\nRegional\no\nBy Rickard Qosser\nFriday, August 17, 1945\ni jr\ni- S\nViews\nLb\u00ae jU\nI\nWe of the labor movement are looking for\nward to peace, for war never has, nor never\nwill be a good thing for those who work for a\nliving. We are anxious to return to the days\nOf peace in which we can seek to gain the\nthings for which we have been seeking and\nmove forward to greater security in a. world\nof peace.\nIt is too early to tell just what is going to\nhappen in the next few months, because we\ndo not know what Congress is going to do or\nwhat the President may have in mind. The\nOnly thing about which we are certain is that\n\u2022we must move quickly to resume peacetime\nproduction and not permit the sudden coming\nof peace to bring about a major depression.\nWORKERS CONCERNED\nWorkers who have been greatly instru\nmental in bringing the war to its victorious\n'ending are greatly concerned over what is now\ngoing to take place. For the past 44 months\nthey have worked long hard hours making the\ninstruments of warfare to destroy our enemies,\ntheir cities, transportation systems and indus\ntrial plants. They now want to produce as\nfully for peace and all the things that go with\nit as they did for war.\nFor the past 44 months the people of this\nnation have cooperated in the greatest single\nproduction effort in the history of the world.\nBy their cooperation they not only brought\nabout the miracle of production needed to save\nthis country but armed our allies and gave\nthem the things they required to defeat the\nItalians and Germans, and now the Japs.\nWhat was done for war must be done for\npeace.\nOUR FUTURE\nnfl\n7\n.^\u00b12^\u2019\nDirector Region 2B, UAW-CIO\nThe war is over and all of us are glad that\nat last there will be an end to the bloodshed JT\nand honors which has marked the past years,\nIt is the feeling of the leadership of the (1\nunions that what happens to the peace is going\nto depend upon what occurs to labor here and\nelsewhere. If the workers are provided with\n/jobs, living wages, increased benefits and se\ncurity this will become a happier world than\nit ever was before.\nIf the people of this and other countries\nare victims of periodic depressions, mass un\nemployment and want in the midst of a world\nof plenty, we can expect further wars, and,\nwith the discovery of the atomic bomb, pos\nsible destruction of whole nations.\nIt appears to me that we must move as\nquickly now that we face the reality of peace\nas we did when the war was thrust upon us.\nWe have another emergency, this time a peace\nemergency which we must meet and solve in\norder \u2019to secure the peace which we have at\nlast won. -t.\nOur people have earned the things for\nwhich they ask. They have fought a good?\nbattle and they deserve and must have the\nfruits of victory\u2014jobs for all at high wages,\nand the opportunity to live in a decent and\nmore secure world.\nFrom The Desk\nMelvin Schultz Tj\nPresident,\nLocal 12. UAW-C1O SMI fl\nI want to take this means of, personally,\nthanking the Membership of Local No. 12 at\nthe Auto-Lite Plants for having desired to re\nmain a part of Local No. 12 and I am quite\nsure for having expressed a determination that\nfrpm here on they will become more active\nin their aid to the many smaller Units of the\nLocal and in helping to build our Organization\nbigger and better.\nIt is my sincere desire that the rank and\nfile membership will attend your Auto-Lite\nUnit meetings with a feverish desire to ad\nvance a sound program for the best interest of\neveryone in your plant. Certainly, the people\nat Auto-Lite are long overdue in obtaining a\nsizeable v^age increase from an Incorporation\nwhich is perhaps one of the wealthiest in our\nCommunity. Local No. 12 looks to the newly\nactivized members of the Auto-Lite to see that\ncooperation does take place between the Unit\nand the Local on a full scale and to see that\nthe Local is not merely the excuse for some\none\u2019s failing to put forth a proper effort.\nNormal procedure as it has been known in\nLocal No. 12 for these many years calls for\nthe Unit Membership to take action in their\nUnit meeting instructing their elected repre\nsentative to bargain with the Management for\nyour request. If no results are accomplished\nby your Committee, request should then be\nforwarded to Local No. 12 1 assure you that\nour best efforts will be put forth to obtain the\nbenefits you are deserving of and desire.\nShould the war end and it be a situation in\nwhich the financial backing and moral sup\nport of Local No. 12 is neede in your argu\nments with your Company, you shall have it.\nI know of no better way for the membership\nof the Auto-Lite Unit of Local No. 12 to re\nceive the benefits of Local No. 12 then that\nwhich I have expressed here. It only remains\nto have all of your Officers, Committees, and\nRepresentatives work in close cooperation\nwith the Officers, Committees, and Reprcsenta\nof Local No. 12,'in order that your aims can\nbe achieved.\nThe question which has just been settled\nat your plant, I think, is evidence and proof\nenough that within the U.A.W.-C.I.O. we have\nreal Democracy and that the majority are\ngiven the opportunity of determining the\ncourse which any group of people are to fol\nlow. This Democracy is known in no other\nUnion in our Country. It is up to all of us to\npreserve it. Only the active participation of all\nUnion-minded people can see us through the\ntrying days of the post-war period.\ny","height":"26862","width":"20418"}}
